Commentary: Taskin steams in from over the wicket and starts off on a good length, shaping away, outside off, Abdullah Shafique shoulders arms.

Commentary: More like it by Taskin! Taskin angles it into the right-hander from over the wicket as he bashes the hard length, on the off-stump line, Abdullah Shafique plays for the angle as he looks to keep it out with a straight bat. The ball holds its line and whizzes past the bat. The keeper, Litton Das collects it around his face.
Default_Commentary: 0.4: Taskin Ahmed to Abdullah Shafique, No run.

Commentary: Taskin goes full this time and gets the ball to swing away, inviting the batter for the drive. Abdullah Shafique resists and lets it go through to the keeper.
Default_Commentary: 0.5: Taskin Ahmed to Abdullah Shafique, No run.

Commentary: OUT! CASTLED! Instant impact for Taskin Ahmed on his return to the Test side after more than a year! A peach of a delivery to see the back of Abdullah Shafique for a duck. Taskin charges in from over the wicket and lands it on a good length, around the sixth stump line, Abdullah Shafique presses half-forward and looks to defend it right under his eyeline. The ball jags back in a long way off the deck and cuts Shafique in half. Beats the batter on the inside edge and it goes through the gap between the bat and the pad to rattle into the top of the off pole. Taskin is thrilled to bits as he lets out a roar.
Default_Commentary: 0.6: Taskin Ahmed to Abdullah Shafique, OUT! b Taskin Ahmed.
Howout: b Taskin Ahmed

Commentary: OUT! LBW! An early breakthrough for Bangladesh right after the Lunch break. A huge confident appeal by Mehidy for LBW, and the umpire raises his finger. Shan Masood, after a brief chat with his partner, Saim Ayub, goes upstairs and challenges the on-field decision. Mehidy continues from around the stumps and drops in a length delivery on the middle and leg stump channel, Shan Masood weighs on the back foot and looks to nudge it away with soft hands to the leg side but plays over the line of the ball as the ball pitches and then spins away to brush the front pad first and then raps him on the back pad. No bat involved on UltraEdge and the Ball Tracking shows three reds with the ball hitting the middle and leg stumps on the projection. Pakistan burn a review and they are 107/2.

Commentary: OUT! STUMPED! First Masood and now Ayub, Mehidy Hasan has gotten both set batters. Saim Ayub runs out of patience and has thrown his start away. Mehidy comes from around the wicket for the left-hander and loops it up, on a nagging length, outside off. Saim Ayub sees the ball tossed up above his eyeline and gets tempted in the flight. He skips down the track and swings to go back over the bowler's head. He takes the risk of hitting against the turn and fails to get to the pitch of the ball. The ball spins away to go past him and the keeper, Litton Das does the rest. It is refereed upstairs and the third umpire first confirms that Das has collected the ball with his gloves behind the stumps and then proceeds to check for stumping where Ayub is short of his crease despite his attempt to turn around and put the dive in. Bangladesh with some quick inroads and Pakistan has now slipped from a comfy 107/1 to 122/3 in the span of just 6 overs.

Commentary: OUT! TIMBER! Taskin Ahmed has the last laugh as he sends back Saud Shakeel who had just started to look settled in. Taskin drags the length back and gets the ball to jag back into the left-hander a long way from just outside the off stump. Saud Shakeel looks to make some room and slice it again but the ball nipping back gets Shakeel into a weird position as he gets cramped up for room. Gets an inside edge and it drags back onto the stumps. Taskin Ahmed gets his second wicket and is all pumped up. Shakeel couldn't make the most of his second life after being dropped when was on 1 by Mehidy Hasan.

Commentary: OUT! PLUMB IN FRONT! Shakib Al Hasan gets the big wicket of Babar Azam with not much time left before Tea. Shakib stays around the wicket and gets the ball to slide on with the arm and this skids through as well, on a fuller length, at the stumps. Babar Azam misreads the length as he goes on the back foot to a full delivery which he could have played on the front foot. Babar tries to work it across the line but the ball keeps coming on with the arm to beat him on the inside edge and pings him on the front pad. Babar does not opt for a review and goes for 31. Pakistan are 179/5.

Commentary: A loud shout for caught behind but the umpire is unmoved! After a long chat with the keeper and the bowler, Najmul Hossain Shanto takes the review with just a second left on the timer. This was pushed through by Shakib Al Hasan, on a nagging length, Agha Salman played for the non-existent turn and got beaten on the inside edge. The ball went through the gap between the bat and pad and the keeper, Litton Das took it on the second attempt. The UltraEdge has rolled in and it shows no spike. Bangladesh lose their second review. They have only one left now.

Commentary: FOUR! Now then! Has this come off the pads? The on-field umpire has given it as runs. After a deliberation, Najmul Hossain Shanto takes the review. Nahid Rana spears in a fullish delivery, on off, Agha Salman gets squared up as he looks to clip it away off his pads. It looks to have come off an outside edge before it raced to the right of the keeper and went past the left of the man at first slip. Yes, UltraEdge confirms that it has indeed come off the outside edge. The replays show that Litton Das had moved way far down the leg side in anticipation and had he been in his normal standing position, it could have been a chance for him. Bangladesh have now lost all their reviews.

Commentary: DROPPED! A tough chance put down by Shadman Islam! This is pushed through by Mehidy, on off, on a nagging length, Khurran hangs his bat out to defend but gets an outside edge that goes low to first slip. Shadman at first slip dives low to his left but the ball clips his fingertips and rolls behind. Agha Salman comes charging for the third run as the throw comes in from the deep. The keeper, Litton Das collects the throw and without even looking at the stumps, deflects the throw onto the stumps at the batting end. The third umpire is called into action for the run out check but the replays show that Salman is in by then.

Commentary: OUT! LBW! A loud shout and the finger is raised! Shakib Al Hasan walks up to his partner and after having a chat, he takes the review. Importantly, it has been given on-field, so, the ball just has to clip the stumps for the decision to be upheld. Khurram Shahzad bowls it on a length from around the wicket, shaping back in, on middle and leg, Shakib Al Hasan's head falls over to the off side as he tries to get across and clip it off his pads. A risky decision to play across the line given the movement on offer this morning. The ball comes back in to beat the inside edge and rap Shakib on the front pad. There is nothing on UltraEdge and the Ball Tracking shows the ball to be clipping the leg stump. The on-field decision will stand and Bangladesh slip further in trouble. They are now 26/6, trailing by 248 runs.
Default_Commentary: 11.3: Khurram Shahzad to Shakib Al Hasan, OUT! lbw b Khurram Shahzad.

Commentary: OUT! CAUGHT! Saim Ayub grabs a very well-judged catch to end a brilliant innings from the lone warrior of Bangladesh, Litton Das! Agha Salman fires the ball into the pitch as he sees Litton Das stepping down the track for a big shot. Litton Das gets this one off the the toe end, a rare sight in this innings from him and it goes flat and low to the right of long on. Saim Ayub at long on makes a good sprint to his right and dives, grabbing the ball with both hands inches above the ground. A much-needed breakthrough for Pakistan. End of a marathon innings from Litton Das as he falls for 138 with Bangladesh trailing by 12 runs.

Commentary: A big shout for LBW but the umpire shakes his head. After a deliberation, Najmul Hossain Shanto takes the review. Was it going down leg or was there bat involved? A searing yorker by Mahmud, at the toes. Agha Salman hurriedly gets his bat down to keep this one out. It looked like he got beaten on the inside edge and wore it on the toes at first glance. After a long wait, the UltraEdge comes up and it shows that the ball has hit Salman flush on the toes and there is no bat involved. Over to Ball Tracking now. Still waiting, says the third umpire. The impact is in line but the ball is clipping the leg stump. It is umpire's call and the on-field decision is upheld. Bangladesh keep their review. A decision that could have gone either way has gone in the favour of Pakistan.

Commentary: Play and a miss! Ali bowls it full and outside off, Zakir Hasan sees the width on offer and tries to cash in on it. Goes for the drive but gets beaten as the ball goes under the bat. The ball just about carries to the keeper, Sarfaraz Ahmed. Would you believe it? The replays have rolled in and the UltraEdge shows a small spike as the ball passes the bottom edge of the bat. Surprisingly, no one from Pakistan heard it.

Commentary: OUT! CLEANED HIM UP! An absolute beauty from Mir Hamza! Pakistan get the reward for building the pressure. Hamza stays over the wicket and angles the ball into the left-hander, on the off stump line, on a good length. Zakir Hasan shapes up to play for the angle as he looks to defend it in front of his body with a straight bat. The ball holds its line, enough to beat the outside edge and clatters into the top of the off pole. Zakir goes for 40. Bangladesh are now 58/1, requiring 127 more runs to win.

Commentary: DROPPED! A tough chance for Agha Salman at second slip, but had there been a third slip, it would have gone straight into his hand. Hamza bowls it on a back of a length, in the channel on off. Shadman Islam hangs back and throws his hands at the delivery. Gets an outside edge that flies at waist height to the left of Agha Salman at second slip. He flings himself to his left but fails to cling on as the ball hits his outstretched left palm and goes down. A big moment in the game. Shadman gets a reprieve on 17.

Bangladesh need another 118 runs to win.

Commentary: FOUR! And that's it! Shakib Al Hasan seals the win with a boundary! The two senior players see Bangladesh home. Jubilant scenes in the Bangladesh camp as Najmul Hossain Shanto and his teammates embrace each other in celebration. Coming to the delivery, this was tossed up, full and wide on off, Shakib Al Hasan reached out in front and cracked the drive through covers for a boundary. Bangladesh win by 6 wickets and complete a 2-0 clean sweep!
